# Day 6 of My Cybersecurity Journey 🚀

Today I focused on learning **Port Scanning using Nmap** in detail — one of the most important skills in networking and penetration testing.

## What I Learned 📚

### 🔹 Introduction to Nmap

* Understanding what Nmap (Network Mapper) is
* Why Nmap is widely used in cybersecurity and ethical hacking
* Real-world use cases of port scanning and network reconnaissance

### 🔹 Port Scanning Concepts

* Open Ports
* Closed Ports
* Filtered Ports
* TCP vs UDP scanning
* Importance of service detection

### 🔹 Nmap Scan Types

* TCP Connect Scan (`-sT`)
* SYN Scan / Stealth Scan (`-sS`)
* UDP Scan (`-sU`)
* Ping Scan (`-sn`)
* Version Detection (`-sV`)
* OS Detection (`-O`)
* Aggressive Scan (`-A`)

### 🔹 Common Nmap Commands Practiced

```bash
nmap <target-ip>
nmap -sS <target-ip>
nmap -sV <target-ip>
nmap -A <target-ip>
nmap -O <target-ip>
nmap -p 1-1000 <target-ip>
nmap -sn <network-range>
```

### 🔹 Enumeration & Reconnaissance

* Discovering live hosts in a network
* Identifying running services
* Detecting operating systems
* Understanding banners and service fingerprints

### 🔹 Nmap Scripting Engine (NSE)

* Basics of NSE scripts
* How automation helps in reconnaissance
* Running default scripts:

```bash
nmap --script=default <target-ip>
```

### 🔹 Key Takeaways

* Port scanning is the foundation of penetration testing
* Proper reconnaissance provides valuable attack surface information
* Nmap is powerful for both network administration and security assessment
* Understanding scan types helps in stealth and efficiency

Excited to continue exploring advanced enumeration and network security concepts. 🔥

